Day 01 (18-June-2026)

🛠️ The 3 AWS Core Concepts to Learn
AWS has hundreds of services, but as a Data Analyst/Scientist, you only need to care about three foundational layers:

IAM (Identity and Access Management): 
How permissions are managed. (Rule #1 of Cloud: Never use your root account for daily tasks; create an IAM user with restricted permissions).

Amazon S3 (Simple Storage Service): 
This is your cloud file cabinet. It’s where raw data files (like CSVs of programmatic ad logs or Kaggle sports datasets) live before they are processed.

Amazon Redshift / Athena: 
The querying layers. Redshift is AWS’s heavy-duty cloud data warehouse (similar to BigQuery), while Athena lets you write SQL queries directly on top of raw files sitting in S3.

The S3 "Data Bucket" Exercise (Hands-on data ingestion task):
- Log into your AWS Console and search for S3.
- Create a "Bucket"
